</article>
</div>
<p>Now letâ€™s get on to the strategies that will help you raise your landing page conversion rates.</p>
<h2>1. Incentivize Your Visitors with an Irresistible Offer</h2>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="cff2bc3d-ae56-4726-a2a1-a1380f6ddded" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/high-converting-landing-pages-C.png" alt="high converting landing pages" width="720" height="464" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Vitacost does a great job of making an offer that helps close the deal right away. Iâ€™m a huge proponent of giving new customers an incentive to <strong>take action right now</strong>, and after about five seconds on the site this enticing offer pops upâ€”a 10 percent discountâ€”and itâ€™s something the main competition is not doing. Given this, Iâ€™d be more inclined to shop with Vitacost since theyâ€™re giving me immediate savings.</p>
<p>Additionally, the page itself gives a clean, well-laid-out impression, and it makes the benefit statement clear: save up to 37 percent on organic foods. Specificity sells, and pinpointing it at this granular level makes it more believable.</p>
<p>Ultimately, the main takeaway here is that <strong>the offer provides visitors with something they can use right now</strong>.</p>
<h2>2: Limit Choices</h2>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="0acb4e0f-0aa7-482b-bda0-6768a193cc2e" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/high-converting-landing-pages-D.png" alt="high converting landing pages" width="545" height="295" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>In this example for project management software, Wrike takes minimalism to the extreme. Often with software youâ€™re given multiple choices, but in this case Wrike limits the offer to one main choice at ten dollars a month, billed annually, with a free plan available. They chose to use very little text and make the offer straightforward and to the point.</p>
<p>In this case they went counter to whatâ€™s normally recommended for <a href="/blog/ws/2016/02/24/landing-pages-for-lead-generation">lead gen</a> situations, which is to use the standard three feature and benefit statements, include a list of plans available, and have a form to fill out.</p>
<p>In addition, this landing page stands out because of the <a href="/blog/ws/2016/06/07/hero-images-guide">eye-catching hero image</a>, and it leverages credibility boosters with the Gartner mention and the big-name brand customers along the footer, both of which are best practices for landing pages.</p>
<h2>3. Provide Customer Service with a Lighter Touch</h2>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="a07276cb-2e31-40f1-9d1c-e9e651e20bf4" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/high-converting-landing-pages-E.png" alt="high converting landing pages" width="720" height="335" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="332e8c53-bf25-4927-9286-35625f90f670" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/high-converting-landing-pages-F.png" alt="high converting landing pages" width="720" height="377" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p><a href="/blog/ws/2016/03/21/live-chat-support">Live chat</a> is nothing new, but in this case American Eagle offers it in a less intrusive way than many others do. Thereâ€™s little more annoying than the chat pop-up that comes out of nowhere like a pushy salesperson. In this case when searching for â€œmenâ€™s shorts,â€ the live chat sits in the corner ready for you if you want it. Of course, you have to give up your email address to use itâ€”American Eagle wants to get something out of the chat, right?</p>
<p>In addition, American Eagle uses a nice header image that highlights their wide selection. We covered <a href="/blog/ws/2016/04/05/product-landing-pages">product-landing-page best practices</a> recently here at WordStream if you want more tips on how to optimize them.</p>
<h2>4. Go for a Test Drive</h2>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="73178b89-a5ef-43b2-9b9f-95322e30d48b" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/high-converting-landing-pages-G.png" alt="high converting landing pages" width="591" height="592" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Webexâ€™s landing page for webinar software really nails it when it comes to the test drive. You can either sign up as an individual or group to see the product in action before you decide to buy. This â€œhands-onâ€ approach helps prospects visualize how theyâ€™d be able to use the software in their own lives, which can be a crucial deal-maker and help <a href="/blog/ws/2016/02/03/increase-sales-online">close sales</a>.</p>
<p>The form is a bit long for my taste and would be something to test for sure. We covered <a href="/blog/ws/2015/07/27/landing-page-forms">landing-page forms</a> last year and it warrants revisiting if you use a form on your landing pages.</p>
<p>In addition, following the three feature and benefit statements, Webex builds credibility a la McDonaldâ€™s by showing a running tally of the number of webinars theyâ€™ve hosted in the last month. This credibility booster falls right in line with what Dr. Rober Cialdini mentions as â€œsocial proofâ€ in his widely read and quoted â€œ<a href="http://www.influenceatwork.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/E_Brand_principles.pdf">Influence: The Psychology of Persuasion</a>.â€ (If you havenâ€™t read the book, I suggest you pick it up soon. Itâ€™s pre-internet but the principles stand the test of time.)</p>
<p>In the book Cialdini mentions that social proofâ€”the fact that other people are using or buying the productâ€”helps new prospects feel at ease about the purchase decision because they know lots of other people are customers too. Iâ€™ll reference more Cialdini later.</p>
<h2>5. Provide Real-Time Social Proof</h2>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="3e2ea6ed-0249-4c82-8d2e-9da162a3cc37" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/high-converting-landing-pages-H.png" alt="high converting landing pages" width="720" height="383" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Similar to Webexâ€™s running tally, Timberwolf Bay, a vintage home furnishings company, posts a running update of orders. You see where the person was and what they bought, and itâ€™s updated in real time.</p>
<p>This little feature builds confidence in the company because, as Cialdini mentions, it implies that people just like you are buying from this website. Who wants to feel like theyâ€™re the only customer on a website? Also, itâ€™s pretty fun to watch the orders pop up!</p>
<p>Another example (below) of this strategy comes from Zingermanâ€™s, a popular food market in Ann Arbor, Michigan, except they put the running tally in the footer:</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="ebae5b52-723a-465e-924a-3d36dfaaeab0" data-langcode="en">
