<h2>6. Use Scarcity and Urgency as Motivators</h2>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="2791f61b-a27c-4e69-bf56-199536d935f3" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/high-converting-landing-pages-J.png" alt="high converting landing pages" width="720" height="527" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Here again Timberwolf Bay does a great job of using another of Cialdiniâ€™s principles: scarcity. When youâ€™re looking for â€œtimberwolf bay automobiles,â€ youâ€™re shown the existing inventory. If youâ€™re dying to get B.B. Korn Race Car, hurry. If you wanted the brass accordion â€œheadlightâ€ sconce, youâ€™re out of luck.</p>
<p>Kidding aside, the real-time quantity updates can motivate people to buy now. Showing that an item sold out implies a) your company moves a lot of product and b) visitors need to take action because products DO sell out. The bottom line here is that scarcity motivates people to buy because we hate to feel like weâ€™re going to miss out on something.</p>
<p>Building off the scarcity theme, we should also consider urgency. When we know a sale ends soon, weâ€™re more apt to buy rather than wait. In the example below, Gilt does a great job with a countdown timer to let people know the sale ends soon, so they better act fast:</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="e5af1a38-f5e9-43b4-a274-73bf80f82bbe" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/high-converting-landing-pages-K.jpg" alt="high converting landing pages" width="800" height="449" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<h2>7. Show the Value</h2>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="a6e795e9-dec8-4664-a049-1520c3987bd6" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/high-converting-landing-pages-L.png" alt="high converting landing pages" width="800" height="415" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Everyone loves a deal, and on this page Eastbay does a good job highlighting how theyâ€™ve slashed the price on â€œmenâ€™s kobe shoes.â€ If Eastbay simply showed the new price, a visitor would have no context to put the price in perspective. Now, a potential customer will hopefully think â€œwow, this is a great deal, I need to take advantage of this.â€ At the very least, the shopper will bookmark this page to buy after doing some comparison shopping.</p>
<p>In addition, Eastbay highlights free shipping prominently in the header, so thatâ€™s even more incentive for the visitor to buy from this landing page.</p>
<p>The bottom line in this case: It pays to illustrate the value.</p>
<h3>A Final Word on High-Converting Landing Pages</h3>
<p>These have been just a few <a href="/blog/ws/2015/06/15/landing-page-inspiration">examples of landing pages</a> that go beyond the basics of effective landing page strategy and execution. To be sure, landing pages and their tactics evolve constantly, and as digital marketers we have to always be testing to see what works.</p>
<p>What other strategies have you seen employed to create high-converting landing pages?</p>
