<h2>3. Use Copy That Speaks to Your Target Audience Specifically</h2>
<p>In the above example, the <a href="/blog/ws/2016/03/14/ppc-ad-copywriting">ad copy</a> speaks the customerâ€™s language. Itâ€™s the type of copy (using words like â€œtough,â€ â€œauthentic,â€ and â€œbreaking pointâ€) Â that gets the target market nodding and saying â€œyes, thatâ€™s me, this is exactly who I am.â€</p>
<p>What makes it go even further is that it excludes people by saying itâ€™s not for everyone â€“ itâ€™s for an elite target market that doesnâ€™t want to wear something that could be bought anywhere. Exclusivity sells.</p>
<h2>4. Test Your Ads (Seriously, Test Your Ads)</h2>
<p>This is no surprise to anyone reading this. We have to <a href="/blog/ws/2016/10/27/facebook-ad-copy-tests">test our Facebook ads</a> all the time. Yes, itâ€™s kind of a pain, but it reveals so much about your customer. And those â€œlearning momentsâ€ carry forward to the rest of your advertising channels.</p>
<p>In Fashleticsâ€™ case, two scenarios were created in which the choice was either free shipping or a percentage discount. Without reading ahead, I bet you can guess which one most consumers chose.</p>
