										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Google AdWords takes the word â€œcompetitiveâ€ to new heights. This fluid auction, fired off whenever someone performs a Google search, provides a platform for advertisers to compete for attention, clicks, traffic, and conversions â€“ in short, for customers.</p>
<p>Too often, however, PPC managers see the need to be competitive as a kneejerk cue to raise bids. Though a top rank <em>can</em> be helpful, and you might have to raise your bids to get there, it doesnâ€™t guarantee clicks, let alone that those clicks will <em>convert</em> â€“ and conversions are what matter most.</p>
<p>This guide will show you how to stand out in this competitive space without reverting solely to bid-pumping tactics. Weâ€™ll examine the digital real estate youâ€™re competing for, what prompts your ads to show there, and specific steps you can take to compete in AdWords.</p>
<h2>Where Searchers Are Looking</h2>
<p>Take a step back and think about where searchers look when they see the SERP (search engine results page) and what influences where their eyes go. Naturally, theyâ€™ll go to the top of the page first because thatâ€™s whatâ€™s in front of them and theyâ€™re expecting the top results to (hopefully) solve their search.</p>
<p>Take this Nielsen Norman Group <a href="http://www.nngroup.com/articles/f-shaped-pattern-reading-web-content/">eyetracking study</a> with heat maps that show typical eye movements as a starting point:</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="6413f0e2-650b-4141-87ea-4694589a8feb" data-langcode="und">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/competing-in-adwords-eye-tracking-1.png" alt="Eye Tracking AdWords" width="568" height="278" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Youâ€™ll notice that the red areas, which indicate the popular viewing areas, form an F-shape. The top of the page gets the most attention first, and then eyes focus along the left-hand side, forming an F-shaped pattern â€“ and all of this occurs in a matter of seconds or fractions of seconds. What this means to you is youâ€™ve got to stand out!</p>
<p>Accordingly, from a PPC perspective, you might assume that youâ€™ve got to be in a top-three position to get clicks â€“ because no one looks at the right side of the page. Nothing could be further from the truth, and hereâ€™s why:</p>
<p>Overall, paid search ads account for six percent of total clicks. But, for keywords with high commercial intent,Â the sponsored results earn about <strong>twice as many clicks</strong> as the organic results. What does this do to the F-shape? It turns it into a backward F in which searchers are looking at the top and <em>right-hand side</em> of the page.</p>
<p>Even further, <a href="/articles/google-ads">our research shows</a> that sponsored ads for high-commercial-intent keyword searches receive 64.6 percent of clicks. In other words, <strong>those searchers looking to buy a specific product are <em>more</em> likely to click the sponsored ads</strong> than organic results. This is in part because Google populates the SERP for these commercial queries with a large proportion of highly compelling sponsored ads, such as Product Listing Ads. These splashy above-the-fold ads include eye-catching images and detailed product information. Theyâ€™re hard for searchers who are shopping to ignore, and they may not even recognize them as ads.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="ac511bc3-f9a8-4b9b-8c02-2e5c3b70bde9" data-langcode="und">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/tablet-computer-product-listing-ads-1.png" alt="Using Product Listing Ads" width="840" height="741" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Now that you know what the digital-real-estate layout looks like, letâ€™s take a look at the variables that drive how you appear there and how you can stand out.</p>
<h2>An Ad Rank Refresher â€“ And Major Update</h2>
<p>Ad rank, or, position, is a simple formula. It is (or used to be) a function of your bid and Quality Score. The timeless, soon-to-be-outdated <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MyBB5h20xoc">video explanation</a> of Ad Rank from Googleâ€™s Hal Varian explains how this works, but hereâ€™s a visual overview of it:</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="79f81988-a818-4f80-b3e6-eb9f6fb4407c" data-langcode="und">
